<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-04T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-04T15:00:00-05:00" n="668" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d668">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/1624a: Telegram</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss> to the Minister in Switzerland</hi>
                                        (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>)</head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-04T15:00:00-05:00">October 4, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                                    </dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>185. Would you telegraph whether in your opinion there is any
                                    probability of the League Council tomorrow deciding that a state
                                    of war exists in Ethiopia. If you consider it advisable, I would
                                    be glad to have you telephone the Department at any time before
                                    noon, Washington Time, tomorrow, Saturday, October 5, that you
                                    might be able to give us the latest developments.</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                                    </signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>